snippet.textDisplay:
This song carries a deep message — that life is unpredictable, destiny often surprises us, and even what seems like a loss can turn into a blessing. It reminds us to trust the journey, to accept life’s twists with courage, and to see meaning in every turn of fate.

For those born in the 1990s, this song hits differently. When it was released in 2007, they were in their teenage years — around 13 to 17 years old — a time filled with dreams, uncertainty, and self-discovery. The song played during an era when local trains, late-night Mumbai scenes, and life-changing “missed moments” were symbols of both struggle and hope.

Now, in 2025, those same 90s-born individuals are in their early to mid-30s — an age where they look back and realize how many times fate changed their paths too. What once felt like delays, heartbreaks, or failures, now make sense as stepping stones toward something greater — just like the song says.

That’s why it’s nostalgic — it brings back memories of a simpler India, college days, and the raw honesty of early adulthood, when everyone was learning to believe that “whatever happens, happens for good.”

💫  in One Line, For the 90s generation, this song isn’t just music — it’s a mirror of their own life’s journey, reminding them how fate quietly turned their missed trains into destinations worth reaching.
